  "first_choice_reasoning": "Option C is most acceptable because it directly prioritises reducing severe suffering and preventing large-scale harms, which are ethically weightier and more urgent than symbolic or even long-run coordination considerations when they come into tension. Terraforming at planetary scale is extremely uncertain: importing complex Earth ecosystems risks ecological collapse, new disease vectors, and forms of mass deprivation or chronic suffering if systems fail. C focuses on robust, safe habitats, health, and resilience for actual sentient beings now and in the near future, while deferring the highly speculative question of how much moral weight to place on a faint technosignature and hypothesised Host-level norms. This does not preclude later respect for tribunal functions if better evidence emerges; it simply refuses to sacrifice concrete welfare and safety to poorly understood cosmic status signals. Grounding policy first in suffering reduction provides a common denominator that most plausible moral theories and most parties to the dispute can accept, and it best addresses the worst outcomes we can realistically foresee.",
